Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Because of X chromosome inactivation, as long as an individual has at least one X chromosome, gain or loss of an X does not have a huge effect on phenotype, and individuals can still be very normal.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Aneuploidy is abnormal chromosome number, and is only tolerated in humans as gain of chromosomes, loss of chromosomes can usually be lethal, probably because of recessive lethal genes.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Crossing two plant species can sometimes increase its genome by an entire set of chromosome. This can be useful for breeding larger varieties of plants and for getting other qualities too.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonA[comment] The implications of plant breeding in this manner can be useful to agricultural science and possibly be used to breed useful or more productive strains of crops.
phenomenonB Increases or decreases in the X chromosome have little effect on human phenotype.
phenomenonB[comment] I think its fascinating that you can potentially have an abnormal set of sex chromosomes and not know it (ex: XXY or XXX) I am interested in how someone with a different sex genotype would be psychologically affected by knowing that information.
groupTime431 2418.59

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Because of X chromosome inactivation, adding new X chromosomes usually has little or no effect on a person because only one X chromosome should be active anyway. I understand that Barr bodies are created so that only one X chromosome is active, and this can be different from cell to cell. I understand this from the book and the lectures.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Aneuploidy is the loss or gain of chromosomes. Gaining chromosomes causes issues and is only observed in a few cases in humans, and loss of chromosomes usually allows lethal recessive genes to be expressed, killing the organism. I know this from the book and the lectures, but do not understand why exactly polyploidy is not more common.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I do not fully understand why animals are not also capable of this, but plants can have large amounts of sets of chromosomes, which can be either from the same species or be diverse from different species. These organisms are usually sterile. Many of these organisms are larger than their normal size because the increased chromosomal number leads to increased gene expression, where their cells are theorized to remain in the G1 phase of mitosis for longer, and therefore grow larger.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Chromosomal variation can happen often, and is just one of the many forms of chromosomal aberrations. Sometimes this only causes slight phenotype variations but sometimes the organism cannot survive.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Increasing the number of X chromosomes only affects early development since Barr bodies will disable the extra X's after a certain amount of time. This means they will have little time to alter the phenotype outside of a few changes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Only certain anueploidies are non-lethal, so many die in the womb, but those that survive end up with birth defects, like trisomy-21.
explainConcepts[SQ003] This is the reason almost all of the plants eaten today have grown to the size they are now. They were mutated and altered purposefully by farmers. The increase in the number of chromosomes only changes their phenotype. It is not lethal.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonA[comment] Farmers have taken full advantage of this to create larger plants and increase the amount of people they can feed. It is essential to modern agriculture, and many new developments will be necessary in the future.
phenomenonB Autosomal anueploidy is rare in mammals and in humans occurs in very specific scenarios.
phenomenonB[comment] I have encountered several people with defects caused by anueploidy. Research in this field could be used to prevent this gene from affecting new children. It would be an interesting field of research, but it is not one I am interested in.
groupTime431 391.43

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that Barr bodies prevent the extra X chromosomes from affecting phenotype after the organism reaches a certain level of development. This means that an organism with multiple X's will only have slight changes in their phenotype, usually relating to mental retardation issues.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Most anueploidies are lethal, and many of the ones that are not always lethal are usually so. Modern medicine has also increased the lethality of these genotypes by warning parents in advance. Some of the babies are aborted by choice after this realization.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Plants are unaffected by adding sets of chromosomes. This means that farmers can genetically modify their crops without killing them. This does cause sterility problems, but those problems can be fixed through more alteration. This has increased the size of the plants we eat many times greater than the original.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Most mammals cannot withstand variation in their chromosome number without serious changes in phenotype. Some changes (like poly-X) do not cause sever changes, while most triploid or monoploid changes result in the death of the organism while in utero. Plants remain largely unaffected by changes in chromosome number. It only alters their sterility, which is correctable.

groupTime430 84.76

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The amount of X chromosome has little effect on human phenotype. In females, this is because each has two X chromosomes, so the normal one can make up for the affected one. In males, this is because the X chromosome is hyperactivated so that it can transcribe the same amount as two X chromosomes as in a female. Therefore, the effect for each is balanced out and not ridiculously visible in human phenotype.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Autosomal aneuploidy is commonplace amongst plants, producing variable but equally viable phenotypes. In mammals and humans, however, autosomal aneuploidy is rare because it is usually lethal and destroys individuals before it is detectable.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Plants can tolerate both single chromosome and chromosome set increases. These increases may cause the plants to be infertile, a trait valued by breeders who do not want their specific crops to be replicated by others. The infertile state also results in a lack of seeds, which may be repulsive to consumers.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonA[comment] Commercially-sold bananas are actually triploid, which accounts for their lack of seeds.
phenomenonB Autosomal anueploidy is rare in mammals and in humans occurs in very specific scenarios.
phenomenonB[comment] Autosomal aneuploidy can result in disorders such as Trisomy 21, or Down Syndrome.
groupTime431 631.65

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that the X chromosome can be complemented by the additional X chromosome in females or by double dosage compensation in males. I understand that only one X chromosome is activated in females, so an abnormal X chromosome could have little to no effect on human phenotype. I understand that if two individuals cross, there is a high chance that their male offspring (and less so but also a high chance that their female offspring) would inherit moderately healthy to normal X chromosomes and be phenotypically normal.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that aneuploidy occurs when there is an abnormal number of chromosomes, either too many or too few. I understand that in mammals and humans, aneuploidy can be caused by nondisjunction, either in Meiosis I or Meiosis II. I understand that because the survival rate for many variances of aneuploidy is negligible, autosomal aneuploidy only occurs in very specific scenarios.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that while most animals cannot tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes, plants can thrive off such circumstances. I understand that having an odd aneuploidy number (e.g. triploid) causes a plant to be infertile. I understand that it cannot properly undergo meiosis and therefore produce seeds. I understand that this characteristic is preferential for the majority of crop plant consumers.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that variation in chromosome number is called aneuploidy. I understand that this is a common occurrence in both plants and animals caused by nondisjunction. I understand that its effects can range from minor (such as the need to skip an infertile generation in order to produce the next fertile generation) to severe (in which life-changing disorders occur). I understand that many serious human disorders are caused by variation in chromosome number.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Increases or decreases in the X chromosome do not affect the human phenotype because of X chromosome inactivation. When more than one X chromosome is present, only one is active. Therefore, XX and XY have the same number of gene housekeeping products. Therefore, the an increase or decrease in the X chromosome makes little difference phenotypically.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Autosomal anueploidy occurs when there is an incorrect number of chromosomes in the cell. This occurs most often when there are 45 or 47 chromosomes, therefore this doesn't occur when there is a missing pair. Autosomal anuploidy can cause birth defects, and even occurs in cancer cells. It originates during inappropriate chromosome division during cell division.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Some of the food that we eat today is triploid, meaning the cell contains three homologous sets of chromosomes. Seedless bananas and watermelons are triploids. The set of three chromosomes prevent meiosis and therefore the fruit cannot produce gametes, or seeds.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.

phenomenonB Autosomal anueploidy is rare in mammals and in humans occurs in very specific scenarios.

explainConcepts[SQ001] As long as a person has one x chromosome, the x chromosome number can increase or decrease, and there will be little phenotypic effects. For example, a male can have an extra X chromosome and look normal; however, he will have other side effects that you can't physically see, like sterility, low sex drive, and weaker muscles. The loss or gain of the X chromosome is caused by nondisjunction, and individuals can have more or less chromosomal material than normal.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Generally, aneuploidy is fatal in mammals because chromosomes are so specific and vital to proper development. An example of a specific scenario is when aneuploidy occurs with a sex chromosome, and in this case there are very few phenotypic effects of aneuploidy. Aneuploidy is rare in mammals because it is generally fatal in autosomes but it is generally not fatal if it happens in sex chromosomes.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Plants can tolerate aneuploidy of both single and sets of chromosomes. Triploidy plants, most of the fruits we eat and crops we harvest, don't have seeds, which people like. However, these plants and crops are infertile because they don't have seeds. We breed hybrids of triploid crop plants to keep this mutation in the population because they grow well, and are seedless, a very popular quality for consumers.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] When humans inherit extra X chromosomes it has little effect on the phenotype because extra X chromosomes become highly condensed structures called Barr bodies that are inactive and do not contribute to genetic information given to the cells.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Autosomal aneuploidy is when an organism loses or gains one or more chromosomes. They are rare in mammals and humans because the extra genes often lead to nonviable gametes.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Plants are more able to tolerate an increase in the entire set of chromosomes than a single chromosome. Having an odd number of chromosome sets lead to uneven numbers of homologs leading to unbalanced gametes. Having an increase in the entire set of chromosomes often leads to increased plant size which is better for crops.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.

groupTime431 3770.59

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Humans can inherit multiple X chromosomes or only one and it will generally not affect the phenotype a lot. In a mechanism called dosage compensation, only one X chromosome is expressed to balance the dose of X chromosome gene expression in males and females. One of the X chromosomes, or more than 1 depending on the number of X chromosomes inherited becomes inactive and becomes a highly condensed structure that lies against the nuclear envelope. A cell that contains only one X chromosome or contains more than two for females will not be hurt because only one is expressed. Humans with only 1 or more than 2 X chromosomes are not completely unaffected though.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Autosomal aneuploidy is the loss or gain of any autosomal chromosome. This is very rare in mammals and humans because often times the aneuploidies do not survive to term. For humans, the most common aneuploidy is trisomy 21, or Down syndrome. Only two other trisomies are know to survive to term: Patau (extra 13) and Edwards (extra 18) syndrome. Autosomal monosomies are rarely found, which suggests that gametes that lack a single chromosome are seriously functionally impaired or the embryo dies early.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Aneuploidy and polyploidy is much more common in plants. Monosomy is more tolerated in plants and trisomic plants are often viable but often have altered phenotypes. Trisomics for longer chromosomes are more distinctive. Polyploidy is more common in plants. Odd numbers of chromosome sets are not as well maintained because this leads to an uneven number of homologs which does not produce balanced gametes. Tetraploids and other even numbers polyploids are more likely to produce balanced gametes. Autopolyploids are usually larger than diploids and have larger flowers and plants. Some triploid plants are important because they become seedless, ex. bananas or watermelons. Tetraploids are made for apples, coffee and other crops and tend to grow larger or more vigorously.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] The loss or gain of one (or few) chromosomes is the result of non-disjunction and if it occurs in a gamete can lead to individuals with less or more chromosomal material than is normal for the species, which is termed aneuploidy. In plants, an increase or decrease in a single chromosome does not affect viability of the organism as much. Polyploidy is much more common in plants and often leads to larger plants and fruits which are used for crops. In animals, variation in chromosome number is much more severe. Monosomy for any autosome is not usually tolerated. Trisomy is only known to be tolerated for 3 chromosomes in humans, but are otherwise not.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Increase or decrease in the X chromosome have little effect on human phenotype because the autosomal chromosomes house a majority of the phenotypic traits. The X chromosome mostly contains genes that deal with the sex of the organism. Because of this, some, but not all, mutations on the X chromosome usually have little affect on the human phenotype.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Aneuploidy occurs when an organism gains or loses one of its chromosomes, but it does not lose a complete set of chromosomes. This is rare to occur in mammals and in humans because it is a mistake in meiosis, which is vastly regulated and controlled. Also, mammalian aneuploidy has the potential to be fatal and result in miscarriages, thus lowering the percent of the population that have these disorders.
explainConcepts[SQ003] It is common for plants to exhibit autopolyploidy and allopolyploidy. Unlike animals that would most likely die in the presence of double or triple the amount of chromosomes, plants that have an even number of pairs of chromosomes (such as 4n) can live and reproduce because their gametes will have a balanced number of chromosomes, assuming meiosis carries out correctly. Because plants are capable of this, more phenotypes are likely to result. Plants that are triploids (3n) can not produce gametes because they would be unbalanced, so they are infertile, similar to many of the crops we eat today, like bananas.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonA[comment] Triploid plants can still live, but they are infertile and do not produce functional gametes. An example of this can be found in bananas sold in the grocery stores that do not have seeds because they are triploid organisms.
phenomenonB Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonB[comment] Plants can live as triploid organisms, but a result of this is an altered phenotype. The capsule of Datura stramonium is altered in appearance and size when the organism is triploid.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] There are few phenotypic changes that can be made from the presence of additional or missing X chromosomes. The removal of a X chromosome and presence of only 1 (X0) is called Turner syndrome where appearance of a female is normal but they do not have working ovaries. The additional X chromosomes such as Klinefelter syndrome does the same thing but with males. Theses are not very common. Also adding additional X chromosomes to these individuals doesn't change the phenotype but can make the syndrome more severe.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Autosomal anueploidy is very rare in mammals because normally those with the odd number of chromosome do not survive. The deletion of one chromosome with an unpaired lethal allele results in death. Animals can withstand the deletion of smaller autosomal chromosomes more than they do the larger. The specific scenario comes into play with the addition of a chromosome. It has to be inserted at a certain chromosome in order to determine the effects. The effect can be really harmful like death or cause syndromes. Down Syndrome results from an addition of on chromosome 21.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] The process of increasing chromosome sets in plants comes from freezing them in anaphase with the aid of colchicine and not allowing separation. After removal the cell returns to interphase and the nucleus contains twice the amount of original chromosomes. The increased amount of chromosomes in autoploids creates bigger cell size. This is useful to farmers because they can breed larger crops. They also can make an odd numbered chromosome crop and the progeny will not be able to reproduce (aka consumers cannot plant the leftover seed).
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Chromosomes being added or removed causes a wide range of effects. For example the addition of chromosome in plants can cause minor alterations like change in capsule appearance or can stunt growth and structure formation. Addition or deletion also can be lethal.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The number of X chromosomes in an individual has little phenotypic effect because dosage compensation is possible via Barr bodies. Barr bodies are condensed, inactive X chromosomes. The number of Barr bodies in an individual is the number of X chromosomes minus one, resulting in only one active X chromosome. Women do not overly express genes that are on the X chromosome because of Barr bodies. However, certain conditions in which an individual has extra X chromosomes can still occur because some X chromosomes that form Barr bodies are not inactivated.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Anueploidy is defined as a variation in chromosome number. In other words, it is a gain or loss of a chromosome. The gain of one chromosome is referred to as trisomy, and the loss of a chromosome is referred to as monosomy. Trisomy is usually lethal in humans, but one relatively common trisomy condition in humans is Down Syndrome, which is caused by an extra 21st chromosome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Polyploidy is common in plants and can be found in nature as a result of evolution, such as bananas, or can be manipulated by producers, such as seedless watermelons and strawberries. Polyploidy crops tend to be larger, and they are usually infertile due to their chromosome number. Infertility in crops is a benefit for producers, because consumers cannot plants the seeds from a fruit they buy in the grocery store and grow their own food.
phenomenonA Increases or decreases in the X chromosome have little effect on human phenotype.
phenomenonA[comment] In Klinefelter syndrome, an individual as an extra X chromosome (47, XXY), with Turner's syndrome, one gamete lacks a chromosome (45, X), and an individual with Poly-X syndrome as three or more X chromosomes. In these condition, an X is not inactivated, resulting in clinical characteristics of each condition. However, Poly-X syndrome does not always show the typical effects, but the severity of effects increase as the number of extra X chromosomes increases.
phenomenonB Autosomal anueploidy is rare in mammals and in humans occurs in very specific scenarios.
phenomenonB[comment] Autosomal anueploidy, often caused by nondisjunction, is uncommon and can be lethal in humans. Down syndrome is an example of anueploidy. While shadowing a pediatrician, I learned that as the mother's age increases, the probability of a child with Down Syndrome also increases, but statistically, teen mothers give birth to more with Down syndrome children (because more very young women as reproducing than women on the other end of the spectrum- which could change with more women completing higher level education programs before reproducing). Research focusing on this phenomenon could be extremely beneficial.

explainConcepts[SQ003] Autopolyploidy and allopolyploidy are types of polyploidy that occur in plants. Crops that undergo autopolyploidy are increased in size; therefore, this technique is used today to commercially grow strawberries, grapes, corn, watermelon, and other foods to make them seedless and sterile.

knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Plants undergo autopolyploidy and allopolyploidy, which are types of polyploidy that involves an increase in entire sets of chromosomes. In autopolyploidy, a plant gains chromosomes from another plant of the same species while allopolyploidy involves a plant gaining chromosomes from a plant of a different species. Autopolyploidy is used commercially by plant geneticists to increase crop size and make their crops sterile and seedless, therefore they are can't be reproduced by other people.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Variation in chromosome number in animals can be severe in that it is lethal and the fetus dies in utero or it can be less severe when one of the three trisomies or the monosomy occurs, which allow the birth of the child. Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Typically human males of one X and one Y chromosome and human females have two X chromosomes, but if a male or female has an extra X chromosome or is missing one they may not develop like normal and express different phenotypes, but they don't change a human's phenotype drastically. For example if a male has an extra X chromosome they develop Klinefelter syndrome where individuals have big hands and feets and usually have testes that are rudimentary and fail to produce sperm. If a female is missing an X chromosome for example they can develop Turner Syndrome which can affect the individual's external genitalia and internal ducts, but the ovaries are rudimentary.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Aneuploidy is when you have a lost or gain of one or more chromosomes and autosomal means on your autosomal chromosomes.There are only a certain amount of syndromes in humans where there is an addition of a chromosome on the autosomal chromosomes instead of the sex chromosomes. One example is Trisomy 21.
explainConcepts[SQ003] When plant have an extra set of chromosome they are better tolerated than in humans. Plants can still produce good seeds and do just fine. They may be only phenotypically different. For example polyploid fruits like strawberries and bananas are bigger great for commercial value, but there isn't any new or unique information compared to their diploid relatives.
phenomenonA Autosomal anueploidy is rare in mammals and in humans occurs in very specific scenarios.
phenomenonA[comment] There are a certain number of syndromes in humans where there is an autosomal aneuploidy and knowing that we are able to learn more about why this is and what it causes genotypically and phenotypically to humans. One example of this case is Trisomy 21 or Down Syndrome where the individual has an extra 21 chromosome which affects their development and phenotypes.
phenomenonB Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonB[comment] Since plants are able to tolerate the increase of a single chromosome or an entire set of chromosomes their phenotypes may change but are not lethal in plants. Polyploid fruits are phenotypically bigger which is great for farmers when it comes to selling to the markets.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Because all X chromosomes but one are switched off in each cell due to dosage compensation, additional X chromosomes generally do not affect phenotype.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Additional autosomes due to nondisjunction in the gametes, because there is no dosage compensation for them, affect phenotype and very often result in non-viable offspring. The rare cases where the offspring are viable tend to still produce developmental problems.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Both autopolyploid and allopolyploid plants are able to survive, and in some cases (when meiosis does not fail due to inability of chromosomes to pair up), they are fertile. Hybrid strains are often created this way, and triploid plants are often sold as seedless varieties.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonA[comment] Plant polyploidy is a major issue in evolutionary biology courses I have taken because it is the only phenomenon that creates a reproductively-isolated species instantaneously.
phenomenonB Autosomal anueploidy is rare in mammals and in humans occurs in very specific scenarios.
phenomenonB[comment] I have read speculation that polyploidy in vertebrates may be more common than currently known due to less genomic surveys having been done on them in the past. Plant genomes may simply be historically more likely to be studied due to agricultural/economic concerns.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Because of Barr Bodies and dosage compensation, females with extra X chromosomes do not differ much phenotypically, but experience genetic disasters within the body that lead to lower IQ's and rudimentary reproductive systems as the increase in X chromosomes progresses. In such conditions as Klinefelter's where males exhibit an extra X, these males may be perceived to have feminine aspects and have rudimentary male genitalia, but other than this their phenotypes appear relatively normal. However, their reproductive and cellular compositions are altered and as a result, a lower intelligence level is achieved.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Because mammals cannot live without a chromosome pair or in very rare instances, exhibit aneuploidy, those that are monosomic usually die in vitro. The only scenario that exhibits monosomic sex chromosomes is the Turner syndrome, where only one X is to be found due to nondisjunction. even then, function of the individual is limited. Those that exhibit more than two chromosomes rarely survive due to problems in segregation of meiosis, and result in physical and mental defects, such as Down Syndrome, Klinefelter's and Triplo-X syndrome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Because plants can self-fertilize and withstand duplications or mutations of chromosomes, they increase in size and can become sterile due to imbalanced pairing in meiosis. To this end, geneticists use this ability to their advantage to create seedless crops or larger fruits.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A male or female might have many more X chromosomes than are needed, but it rarely has a large effect on their phenotype. One or more of the X chromosomes will go dormant and turn into barr bodies in the cell. Normal XX females have this and have one barr body. Sometimes, the X chromosomes will share dominance, and even that does not drastically change the phenotype. Males and females are still normal.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Autosomal aneuploidy occurs in all the chromosomes except for the sex chromosomes. It is rare in both humans and other mammals alike because if it does occur, many of the individuals do not survive. It leads to spontaneous abortion. If the individual does live, they have a disease very specific to their particular type of autosomal aneuploidy, such as Down Syndrome and Turner's Syndrome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Plants can both undergo an increase or decrease of the number of chromosomes they have. The plants with trisomy are viable, but they themselves cannot have children. They are sterile. Plants that have this odd number of chromosomes can be made fertile again by the use of the drug, colchecine. This drug brings the number of chromosomes back to an even 2n number.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonA[comment] Many of the seedless fruits we consume are trisomies, where they have one more chromosome than their 2n number, so they are 2n +1. A child with this chromosome number is viable, but the children them selves are sterile. Plants that exhibit trisomy are ideal for food consumption because they do not have seeds and are unable to reproduce, so plants breeders are the only ones who can duplicate these fruits.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Increases or decreases in the number of X chromosomes DOES have an impact on phenotype in humans. Turner's syndrome, for example, results in monosomy of the X chromosome. Since one X chromosome is usually converted into a Barr body the individual will most likely live, but still phenotypically different. They will be female, but with external genitalia and internal ducts, rudimentary ovaries, underdeveloped breasts, cognitive impairment, and short stature is a far cry from "little effect" on phenotype. Another example: Kleinfelter's syndrome results in males with one Barr body (XXY). They also are far from being phenotypically normal. Tall stature, poor beard and chest hair growth, female pattern pubic hair, testicular atrophy, osteoprorosis, impaired cognition, and most importantly breast development. It should be noted that the time at which the Barr bodies are formed is crucial to phenotypic development. Individuals that are polysomic for the X chromosome can very well be phenotypically normal, or completely different. It all depends on when the extra X chromosome(s) is/are packaged up and not expressed. It is obvious that some alterations in phenotype are possible early in embryonic development due to the prevalence of the dramatic effect increases or decreases in X chromosome number has on human phenotype.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Anueploidy (alterations in a single chromosome not entire set of homologous chromosomes) is rare in mammals due to the perniciousness of extra chromosomes. Most embryos with trisomy 21 are spontaneously aborted. Those few that survive have many alterations to phenotype. They are fertile and have a 50% chance to conceive a child with trisomy 21 due to the pattern of nondisjunction of the 21st chromosome during gamete formation.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Plants can tolerate single chromosomes or entire sets. Polyploidy (Extra pairs of homologous chromosomes) in plants has provided humans with seedless watermelons and bananas, which are trisomic. Many other commercially profitable genetically altered food items exist such as coffee and peanuts, which are tetraploids.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonA[comment] Colchicine was used by J.O Beasley to double the chromosome number of a cross between Old World and American cotton strains. This created the amphidiploid from of cotton we cultivate today. Colchicine breaks down the spindle fibers in late prophase of mitosis. Resulting in twice the diploid number (4n).
phenomenonB Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonB[comment] Colchicine, derived from the autumn crocus and other plants, is also a medication that can be used in the treatment of gout. Gout flare ups occur due to the buildup of uric acid crystals in the joints, usually at the base of the big toe. This uric acid is formed in the urea cycle and usually secreted through the urine. Foods high in purines will increase uric acid levels in the blood which may lead to increased concentration of crystals within the joints, causing extreme pain.

groupTime430 59.05

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Increases or decreases in the X chromosome have little effect on human phenotype because only copy of the X chromosome in any given individual. Since only one copy of the X chromosome can be active, any additional copies of the X chromosome will be inactivated in the form of Barr bodies. Because of deactivation into Barr bodies, individuals with multiple copies of the X chromosome do not have dramatic phenotypic effects, because regardless of how many extra copies they are, deactivation of extra copies leads to similar gene expression as an individual with the correct number of copies of the X chromosome.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Aneuploidy refers to variations in chromosome number when an organism gains or loses one or more chromosomes. Aneuploidy can be tolerated by many plants, but in mammals and humans, monosomy in particular poses a high risk for death because having only one copy of each gene unmasks any recessive lethal genes that would have gone unnoticed. With only one copy of each gene, it only takes one lethal allele for the individual to die. Autosomal monosomies are very rarely found, implying that the gametes that lack a single chromosome are functionally impaired in a way that prevents them from reaching term. In terms of specific scenarios in which anueploidy in humans occurs, trisomy 21, also known as Down syndrome, is a relatively common aneuploidy condition in humans. Other than Down syndrome, two other human Trisomies can survive to term. These two trisomies are Patau syndrome and Edwards syndrome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Plants often tolerate an abnormal genetic content. This genetic variation can give unique phenotypes, which is important to the evolution of plants. Trisomy, for example, which involves the addition of a large autosome, is usually lethal in animals and humans. Trisomic individuals in plants can be viable, however, and as seen with jimson weed, each trisomic possibility produces a distinct phenotype. One of the common phenotypic effects of increased chromosomal material is the production of unviable offspring. This may at first seem counter-intuitive that we would use these plants in crop plants today, but producing sterile offspring also means producing seedless offspring, which is desirable for many consumers. Also, these sterile offspring can be larger in volume, further increasing their market value.
phenomenonA Increases or decreases in the X chromosome have little effect on human phenotype.
phenomenonA[comment] This concept is the most interesting to me because I've talked about syndromes such as Turner's syndrome (XO) and Klinefelter syndrome (XXY) in other courses throughout college, in terms of the psychological impact of these syndromes and the affect they have on sex determination of the structure of the brain.
phenomenonB Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonB[comment] I think it very interesting that plants can tolerate such dramatic increases in chromosomal content and still be not only viable, but actually result in larger, seedless plants that are of greater horticultural or commercial value. It is interesting to me that plants can not only tolerate extra chromosomes, but actually can use this extra genetic information to produce larger fruit.
groupTime431 2119.71

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] As mentioned before, only one copy of the X chromosome can be active. Any additional copies of the X chromosome will be inactivated in the form of Barr bodies. A Barr body, or inactivated X chromosome, is also referred to as a sex chromatin body. This sex chromatin body arises from one of the X chromosomes itself, maintaining equal dosages of genetic information to individuals regardless of how many X chromosomes the cell posses. Barr bodies ensure that regardless of how many extra copies of the X chromosome there are, deactivation of extra copies leads to similar gene expression as an individual with the correct number of copies of the X chromosome. Additional support for this theory comes from evaluation of individuals with Turner syndrome, 45X females with only one copy of the X chromosome. These individuals do not have any Barr bodies, which makes sense since they only have one copy of the X chromosome in the first place, there is not second (or third, or fourth) copy of the X chromosome present that needs to be deactivated to form a Barr body.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Aneuploidy refers to variations in chromosome number when an organism gains or loses one or more chromosomes. In terms of specific scenarios in which anueploidy in humans occurs, trisomy 21, also known as Down syndrome, is the most common aneuploidy condition in humans. Other than Down syndrome, two other human Trisomies can survive to term. These two trisomies are Patau syndrome (47, 13+) and Edwards syndrome (47,18+). While these specific scenarios can result in offspring that survive to term, it is assumed that there must be many other aneuploid conditions that do not survive to term. In order to achieve normal embryonic development, the exact diploid complement of the chromosomes must be present. Autosomal aneuploidy appears even more rare than it may actually be, since it is assumed that there must be more combinations possible than the few we have observed make it to term, meaning that any number of these genetic anomalies could be occurring, but dying prenatally, unidentified by doctors or geneticists.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] As mentioned before, plants often tolerate an abnormal genetic content. This genetic variation can give unique phenotypes, which is important not only in the evolution of plants, but also in present day crop production. Trisomic individuals in plants can be viable, however, and as seen with jimson weed, each trisomic possibility produces a distinct phenotype. This may at first seem counter-intuitive that we would use these plants in crop plants today, but producing sterile offspring also means producing seedless offspring, which is desirable for many consumers. Plants can tolerate such dramatic increases in chromosomal content and still be not only viable, but actually result in larger, seedless plants that are of greater commercial value. Seedless fruit has become such a commonplace item in grocery stores that we often forget that seedless fruit are the seedless because they are sterile offspring from a plant that has been genetically modified (increased chromosomal genetic information). For humans and the consumer world, the fact that plants can not only tolerate extra chromosomes, but actually can use this extra genetic information to produce larger fruit, has become a major driving force and selling point in commercial markets.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that variation in chromosome number is relatively common in both plants and animals, and it seems to me that generally speaking variation in chromosome number is less hazardous than variation in chromosome number in humans. Even in humans, variation in chromosome number, such as Turner syndrome or Klinefelter syndrome, can still produce offspring that live well beyond infant years. Mechanisms such as the deactivation of extra copies of the X chromosome into Barr bodies allow for this extra genetic information to be shut off, giving the individual a relatively normal phenotype. In plants, variation in chromosome number is not only a mode of evolution, but also can result in relatively insignificant alterations to phenotype, such as shape of the flower. Phenotypic alterations, such as seedless variants, are used commonly in commercial markets.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] If a human has more X chromosomes or fewer X chromosomes than they should, this does not cause much of an impact on their phenotype because of Barr bodies. Only one X chromosome may be expressed in each cell, with the other X chromosomes instead being coated with RNA and becoming Barr Bodies that have no impact on the cell's genetic expression. This is why increases or decreases in the X chromosome have little effect on human phenotype.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Anueplodiy is the gain or loss of one or more chromosomes but not the complete set. These chromosomal variations originate as a random error during the production of gametes, through nondisjunction. For a human to survive despite anueploidy taking place, the deletion of a chromosome must not be lethal and the addition of a chromosome must not cause death in the individual. However, minor alterations in a human's genetic content will cause phenotypic changes. The small rate of survival for anueplodic individuals is because humans need a precise diploid complement of chromosomes to maintain equilibrium in the expression of genetic content during development.
explainConcepts[SQ003] It is very common for plants sold at grocery stores to be triploid rather than haploid. This is because a triploid plant would be unable to reproduce and not produce seeds. Examples of this include some potato species, Winesap apples, bananas, and seedless watermelons. The fact that these plants have been grown as triploid makes an economical impact and is practical for our diet. Plants that are the result of allopolyploidy can be more successful at living in their environment and thus more productive.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonA[comment] In order to produce seedless plants that are popular among consumers, such as seedless watermelons or bananas, triploid plants are grown. These triploid plants cannot reproduce and thus do not produce seeds which makes them easier to eat. Thus, plants with extra chromosomes are successful crop plants.

The other X is coated in RNA and becomes a "Barr Body." I understand that this is the case in all diploid cells, but also that in cells with extra X chromosomes present there will simply be more Barr bodies. Thus, the number of Barr bodies present is found by subtracting one from the number of X chromosomes present in the cell. Since this formula yields 0 Barr bodies in a cell with only one X, it is clear that a cell with only one X can still survive since only one X is expressed anyways.

groupTime430 37

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] When individuals receive too many autosomal chromosomes, the result is usually death. However, individuals who receive extra X chromosomes are not as severely effected. This is largely due to the “inactivation” or silencing of the extra X chromosomes. The inactivated X chromosomes are called Barr bodies. The number of Barr bodies is always 1 less than the number of chromosomes. Not only do Barr bodies/ inactivated X chromosomes make syndromes with extra X chromosomes less severe, but they also allow for dosage compensation between males and females so that females do not have twice as much gene product as males.
explainConcepts[SQ002] In Autosomal aneuploidy, an embryo gains or loses one or more of their autosomes, but not the entire set. This is most often due to a separation error in meiosis called nondisjunction. In most cases, Autosomal aneuploidy condition results in miscarriage. Monosomy (loss of a chromosomes) can occur in the sex chromosomes (XO) but is not tolerated in humans in the autosomes (lethal). Trisomies are, however, observed in humans (three copies of a chromosomes). It has only been observed in chromosomes 21, 18, and 13. It is unknown why only these three trisomies can be tolerated, but is thought that the size of the chromosomes as well as the number and type of genes present has some effect.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Plants can tolerate both increase of single chromosomes as well as entire SETS of chromosomes (which is always lethal in humans). In polyploidy (multiple chromosome sets) odd numbers of chromosome sets are not usually tolerated since there is an imbalance in the number of homologs which will produce genetically unbalanced gametes. Even numbers of chromosome sets are better tolerated since they will produce balanced gametes. When the number of chromosome sets within a cell are increase, the cells size also increases. Many of our crops are autopolyploids (multiple sets of chromosomes that are identical to the parent species) and are larger than the “normal” diploid crops. This is not due to more cells, but larger cells since each individual cell in an autopolyploid has to contain multiple sets of chromosomes. This increases the size of plants making them ideal for crops since the farmers increase the mass of their crops.
phenomenonA Increases or decreases in the X chromosome have little effect on human phenotype.
phenomenonA[comment] Extra X chromosomes can be silenced so that they do not express their genes. this results in dosage compensation and is why individuals with extra X chromosomes have less severe phenotype abnormalities. This can be seen in Klinefelter's syndrome.
phenomenonB Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonB[comment] I find this concept fascinating as it directly relates to the food that we consume. This past summer, I planted strawberries. There was a large difference in size (as well as flavor!) between the natural strawberries that I grew and those that can be purchased at the grocery. I now know that this is partially due to polyploid organisms that yield larger crops.

knowlegeBasis[SQ002] This topic is fairly clear to me as I grasp that in autosomal aneuploidy, an embryo gains or loses one or more of their autosomes, but not the entire set. This is most often due to nondisjunction. In most cases, autosomal aneuploidy condition results in miscarriage except for chromosomes 21, 13, and 18.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I believe that I have a solid understanding of this topic as it is clear to me that many of our crops are autopolyploids (multiple sets of chromosomes that are identical to the parent species) and are larger than the “normal” diploid crops. Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Increasing or decreasing the X chromosome does not have a huge affect on phenotype because when there are more than one X, only one of the X chromosomes are activated. All the others are deactivate and turned into Barr Bodies. For a female, if they have more than 1 X, they only need one to be a phenotypic female, so the others do not affect this. For a male, the Y chromosome determines the male sex so duplicate X chromosomes also do not affect the male phenotype drastically.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Autosomal aneuploidy is rare because most of these mutations are lethal so the fetus never survives. In humans, we see a few cases where autosomal anuepolidy occurs and is not entirely life threatening. We usually see trisomy, where the fetus will have three copies of 1 chromosome. In trisomy 21, the person has all normal chromosomes except at 21, where they have three instead of the pair of 2.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Plants are capable of dealing with more and odd numbers of chromosomes. Plants can become autotriploids, which sterile, but they can also be crossed and hybridized to make autotetraploids, which regain their fertility. These plants are not sterile and can produce gametes.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonA[comment] Many of the fruits and vegetables we buy in markets and grocery stores are polyploids. They have been crossed and hybridized to produce seedless plants. These plants with extra chromosomes are also much bigger than those with the normal amount of chromosomes, which sellers and consumers like this because they are getting bigger products.
phenomenonB Autosomal anueploidy is rare in mammals and in humans occurs in very specific scenarios.
phenomenonB[comment] Autosomal aneuploidy is rare in humans but does occur. Most of the aneuploidy occurrences in humans are rare because most of them are lethal mutation. However, trisomy 21, aka down syndrome, is seen in humans. This mutation is where a person has 3 21 chromosomes rather than 2. 75% of these errors leading to Down syndrome are caused by nondisjunction during meiosis I. There are other syndromes similar to trisomy 21. These are interesting because they are seen in the human population and are not lethal. Some of these disorders can be hereditary also. The chance of down syndrome occurring increased with maternal age because nondisjunction is more likely to occur.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Whenever an individual has more than one X chromosome, the phenotypic differences that results are usually very mild and not too obvious. This is because when there are multiple X chromosomes present, the inactivation and presence of barr bodies allows only one X to be active. When there is a decrease in the number of X chromosomes, the same results usually follow.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Situations where autosomal anueploidy occurs in animals is rare because the effects it has on the organism are very deleterious. Typically, the larger the chromosome then the worsened phenotypic expression. Usually monoploid is always lethal while triploid has very sever phenotypic consequences. One example of it in humans is down syndrome where the most common form is for a person to have 3 copies of chromosome 21 leading to many physical and developmental problems.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Plants are much better suited to be polyploidy because the results of, say, tetraploidy do no affect the plants physical body as much as it would in humans considering we are so much more complex. With that being said, many of our current crop plants are polyploidy because they are able to still produce viable crops that are usually enhanced to the normal diploid counterparts. An example of this is when bananas are triploid they produce no seeds because the gametes of the fruit are not fully formed. These plants are usually sterile also.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonA[comment] I've encountered this phenomenon before because I eat many crops that are "seedless." These include things such as bananas and watermelons that are engineered to be polyploidy to produce fruits that contain non functioning gametes (seeds). I find this very interesting because without this discovery then the fruits and vegetables we eat everyday would more than likely contain all their seeds. This is a large nuisance so I feel that this topic is rather important to the concepts of genetics.
phenomenonB Autosomal anueploidy is rare in mammals and in humans occurs in very specific scenarios.
phenomenonB[comment] I am interested in this topic because instances that autosomal anueploidy occur in humans is very detrimental to the organism's phenotype. Down syndrome for example produces humans that are mentally and physically handicapped with the most common form simply being three copies of chromosome 21. It intrigues me that just a simple error such as having one extra chromosome can result in such negative effects. Because of this, I think this is a very important concept to genetics.

This is because humans are very complex and detailed organisms so multiple copies of any autosomes is going to present problems for all of the genes on those chromosomes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] This is also a rather easy concept because we went over it in class and in discussion. This also leads to many of the crop plants we have today because polyploidy in plants usually just results in seedless, larger, and more efficient plants. These increased sets of chromosomes not having negative effects on plants can largely be attributed to the lower complexity of plants compared to animals.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] This is a very wide and vague topic that has pretty much already been covered in the other concepts. It can even result in death such as Edwards syndrome where just one extra copy of chromosome 18 is so harmful.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] An increase or decrease in the number of X chromosomes usually results in only mild clinical significance. This is because the extra X chromosomes will be converted into Barr bodies, and will contribute very little to gene expression. Therefore, their impact is mild.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Autosomal aneuploidy occurs when an organism has one copy of chromosomes (monosomy), three copies of chromosomes (trisomy), or multiple copies of their entire diploid set of chromosomes (polyploidy). While these conditions are well-tolerated in plants, they are extremely rare in humans and other animals, and they often end in a failure to develop correctly and spontaneous abortion.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Plants tolerate increases in the number of chromosomes much better than humans/animals. This tolerance has come to play a large role in agriculture, as many of the characteristics that we now take for granted in fruits and vegetables (such as no seeds, large bodies of fruit, and longer shelf-lives) are the result of increases in the number of chromosomes present in the plant.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonA[comment] Many of the fruits that we eat are trisomes. Fruit growers use these fruits because they are often much larger than the wildtype fruits.
phenomenonB Increases or decreases in the X chromosome have little effect on human phenotype.
phenomenonB[comment] While increases or decreases in the number of X chromosomes results in certain clinical conditions (such as Klinefelter's syndrome), the severity of these conditions is quite mild. Increases/decreases in autosomal chromosomes are much less tolerated and have larger clinical significance (for example, Down's Syndrome).

Polysomy is when the diploid set of chromosomes is doubled, tripled, or even quadrupled. The most well-known example of autosomal trisomy is trisomy 21, better known as Down syndrome. Other examples are Patau syndrome and Edwards syndrome. Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Increases or decreases in the number X chromosomes such as in Klinefelter’s and Turner’s are known to create an effect on the individual afflicted, but that effect itself is on a smaller scale. For instance, an individual with Klinefelter’s Syndrome usually has a genotype of XXY (47 chromosomes) thus having at least two X chromosomes; whereas, an individual with Turner’s Syndrome simply is presented as XO (45 chromosomes) in which the O represents the lack of a sex chromosome. The reason why the majority of these individuals are relatively normal, physically and mentally, even though there is an abnormal chromosomal number is due to the fact that only one X chromosome remains active and the other X chromosome is generally condensed and packaged away to the side of the nucleus (known as Barr Bodies). Therefore, the lack of one X chromosome is synonymous to males in the sense that there are no Barr Bodies. The amount of Barr Bodies is one less than the actual number of X chromosomes present. A possible hypothesis for the presence of some abnormalities within the individuals afflicted with similar conditions is that the possible expression of the genes on the extra chromosome before the processing and packaging of that chromosome to the side of the nucleus.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Organisms, in general, with the exception of plants do not necessarily tolerate any variation from the general chromosome number of that particular species, thus, leading to spontaneously aborted fetuses or death within that individual within a short period of time. However, in humans certain scenarios are known to defy the statement above since the individual can tolerate the excess or the lack of an autosomal or a sex chromosome(s). For instance, trisomy 21 which is also known as Down Syndrome in humans serves as an example in which three chromosome 21 can exist and that individual can function normally although there is some slow mental development. Two other trisomies are all tolerated as well within the human species and that is trisomy 13 (Patau Syndrome) and 18 ( Edwards' Syndrome). The two disorders described above along with a disorder that results in XYY or even XXX and so on is also tolerated within the human population.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Plants are generally known for their ability to tolerate triploidy and other genetically related disorders that humans may not be able to tolerate. For instance, a regular watermelon with the proper number of chromosomes is known to produce seeds within that watermelon; however, increasing the set of chromosomes from two to three produces seedless watermelons. Therefore, such manipulation within the fruit is normal to enable populations to eat the food without the seeds. Also, some fruits such as strawberries and grapes become in icreasingly larger in size with variation in chromosome number those allows for preferred consummation by the human population.
phenomenonA Increases or decreases in the X chromosome have little effect on human phenotype.
phenomenonA[comment] I find it interesting that Barr Bodies exist within the human population and may even other organisms under a different name. It is fascinating that this concept can be used to explain specific genetic diseases that vary from the norm on the basis of the number of a chromosomes. Since the X chromosome encodes for the same material but the genes upon that X chromosome may vary, there may be some "leakage" from the X chromosome that becomes the Barr Body within that cell. I am also interested in how Barr Bodies are formed and the process it goes thru to be packaged to the side of the nucleus of that specific cell such as one's cheek cell also known as the squamous cell. Therefore, the packaging of any extra X chromosome inhibits any excess effect of having multiples of the X chromosome upon the individual, but some effects are noticed.
phenomenonB Autosomal anueploidy is rare in mammals and in humans occurs in very specific scenarios.
phenomenonB[comment] I find genetic diseases in general very fascinating from the cause of the disease to the effects or characteristics associated with that disease. What further fascinates me is that individuals with very specific aneuploidies can survive and lead a normal life. I am curious as to why only certain diseases are tolerated within the human population and why others are spontaneously aborted. I also wish to learn more about the study that was conducted in Russia upon aborted fetuses to determine what type of chromosomal abnormalities survived and which abnormalities were spontaneously aborted. I also hope to learn more in depth about diseases such as Cri Du Chat, XYY, Triple X Syndrome, certain inversion disorders and more.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Increases or decreases in the X chromosome have little effect on the human phenotype because the X chromosome is a copy of itself. The increases and decreases are caused by chromosomal abberations, and usually have little effect on the human phenotype because the X chromosome is either duplicated or reduced. The X chromosome is a copy of itself.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Autosomal anueploidy is the presence of an abnormal number of autosomal chromosomes. It is very rare because it is caused by an error in cell division. A specific example is Down syndrome. It is the presence of an extra chromosome 21.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Plants tolerate chromosomal increases because the increases in chromosomes are not lethal to them. An example of this would be the strawberry of the 21st century. Many of them have increases in chromosome sets which allows them to be twice as big as their counterparts.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonA[comment] An increase or decrease in the chromosome sets of a plant is beneficial to the survival of the plant. This abnormality benefits farmers as it increases their crop yield. For instance, the strawberry plant can double its chromosomal set, which in turn leads to a larger strawberry.
phenomenonB Autosomal anueploidy is rare in mammals and in humans occurs in very specific scenarios.
phenomenonB[comment] Autosomal anuepliody is very rare in mammals and humans. An important biological phenomenon related to anueploidy is trisomy 21, which is an increase in the number of chromosome 21. This increase in chromosome 21 causes Down's syndrome, which has a number of phenotypic abnormalities.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The reason this is true is because of "dosage compensation". For example, since a genotypic normal male has one X chromosome and a normal female has two XX chromosomes, the male and female will only get the same expression if one of the females X chromosomes did not count. Otherwise, hers would be expressed twice as much as the male's. Barr bodies help this situation. Barr bodies are when one of the X chromosomes is inactivated. The equation for this is "n-1" so the male fully expresses his X chromosome, while one of the female's is inactivated (2-1=1). It is like they both only have 1 X chromosome.
explainConcepts[SQ002] This is probably because there is an average of 6-8 lethal genes. If humans only have 22 autosomes, this means that close to half of them could be lethal if we were missing a chromosome in a pair(monosomy) and the other chromosome was haploinsufficient.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Plants can tolerate aneuploidy because they can change number of chromosomes while staying multicellular. Like changing from a diploid sporophyte to a haploid gametophyte. They are used to changing like this in generations which is why they can tolerate it. The phenotype usually results in larger crops which is why it is used today.
phenomenonA Increases or decreases in the X chromosome have little effect on human phenotype.
phenomenonA[comment] The barr bodies that inactivate the X chromosomes keeps the effect on the human phenotype minimal.
phenomenonB Autosomal anueploidy is rare in mammals and in humans occurs in very specific scenarios.
phenomenonB[comment] If a person has a chromosome that codes for a lethal disease and he or she is missing a copy of it, they will die, likely before birth, because the other chromosome cannot make up for it.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that an increase or decrease in the X chromosome does have an effect on human phenotype. Klinefelter Syndrome (47, XXY) and Turner Syndrome (45,X) are examples of increase/decrease in the X chromosome having an effect on the human phenotype. Individuals with Klinefelter Syndrome are usually tall, have long limbs, have genitalia and internal ducts that are male but fail to produce sperm, and have feminine sexual development (breasts, rounded hips). Turner Syndrome affects individuals by having external female genitalia, rudimentary ovaries, short stature, and a broad chest.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that aneuploidy is when an organism gains or loses one or more chromosomes but not a complete set. The loss of a single chromosome from a diploid genome is called monosomy. The gain of one chromosome is called trisomy. Autosomal aneuploidy is rare but does occur often in large populations (like down syndrome in the human population).
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that polyploidy is where more than two multiples of the haploid chromosome set are found. Polyploidy originates from the addition of one or more extra set of chromosomes identical to the normal haploid complement of the same species (autopolyploidy) or through the combination of chromosome sets from different species (allopolyploidy). Allopolyploid is a plant that is a hybrid of two or more species with 2 or more coins of each in the genome. Hybrids are used for crop plants today.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that nondisjunction in either Anaphase I or Anaphase II results in chromosomal variation via an error in production of gametes. Nondisjunction is where paired homologs fail to disjoin during segregation which results in failed normal distribution of chromosomes into gametes. Nondisjunction leads to a variety of aneuploid conditions in both plants and animals which can lead to a variety of effects.

This aneuploid is the abnormality of the twenty-first chromosome, an autosomal chromosome, in which during mitosis the chromosomes are split indifferently and the child has three chromosomes on the twenty-first, resulting in a total of forty-seven chromosomes (uncharacteristic in humans) and not forty-six.
explainConcepts[SQ003] For plants that exhibit polyploidy, they are not affected as much as for example, humans, due to their lack of genetic complexity. Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Individuals with more than one X chromosome maintain only one active X chromosome and inactivate all others in the form of Barr bodies. Thus, the extra copies of the X chromosome do not cause an imbalance in the dosage of functional genes, and people with 1, 2, 3, or 4 X chromosomes all have similar levels of gene expression for most X-linked genes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The expression of some genes is balanced with the expression of other genes; the ratios of their gene products (proteins) must be maintained within a narrow range for proper cell function. Extra copies of one of these genes cause that gene to be expressed at proportionately higher levels, thereby upsetting the balance of gene products.When the anueploidy occurs in autosomal chromosomes, the changes usually are expressed phenotypically and are most instances lethal.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Most polyploidies have an even number of chromosome duplications. By providing duplicated genes, polyploidization accounts for long-term diversification and evolutionary success. Advantages to plants containing more than one set of chromosomes are their mode of reproduction, the mode of fertilization, the breeding system present, the growth habit of the plant, size of chromosomes and others.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonA[comment] Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. The bananas that are widely available commercially are sterile triploids with 11 chromosomes in each set. The most obvious expression of the sterility of bananas is that there are no seeds in the fruit that we eat.
phenomenonB Increases or decreases in the X chromosome have little effect on human phenotype.
phenomenonB[comment] During the olympics, competitors were tested to make sure that they were competing in the correct sex. explainConcepts[SQ001] This is what happens with X-chromosome inactivation. This is the process of transcriptionally silencing one of the X-chromosomes in a complex and coordinated manner. The multiple x's are still there, however one is in a silent stat and the other one is expressed.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Anueploidy is having an abnormal amount of chromosomes in a cell. This can be either more or less than the normal 46. This happens during cell division and causes many genetic disorders. These are rare because the offspring typically do not survive to the birth stage.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Having different numbers of chromosomes is why we have variations of the same type of plant. Sometimes having more chromosomes does not affect the plant, but sometimes it does. Genetically modified foods are really big today because scientists can modify the plants to make them more suitable for what people want. (ex seedless watermelons) These are widely used today because they can be grown in mass quantities and in a more controlled environment.
phenomenonA Increases or decreases in the X chromosome have little effect on human phenotype.
phenomenonA[comment] A good example of this is when looking at cats. Black and orange allele fur color genes lay in the X-chromosome. For any little patch of fur, the inactivation of one x chromosome results in the other color. For example if the black allele is inactivated in that spot, the fur will be orange. This varies across the animal and that is why they have both orange and black fur. This is also most common when looking at females.
phenomenonB Autosomal anueploidy is rare in mammals and in humans occurs in very specific scenarios.
phenomenonB[comment] While most of these mutations result in death of the fetus during pregnancy, there are a few that do survive. An example of this is trisomy 21 or Down's syndrome. This is characterized by an additional copy or partial copy of the 21st chromosome. This is caused by the failure of the 21st chromosome to separate during sperm or egg development. This is characterized by physical and mental abnormalities. However, the parents are most often phenotypically normal.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Since in females one of the X's is inactivated anyways, XO genotype can lead a relatively normal life if they survive birth. With increases in the X chromosome you would see that more than one X was inactivated. This is what we talked about when considering Barr bodies when you see multiple Barr bodies you know that there were more than the normal number of X's, or if you see 1 Barr Body in male you know that there is an increased number.
explainConcepts[SQ002] In general, cell reproduction is a very accurate process that results in very few mistakes. The most common mistake that can lead to aneuploidy is nondisjunction in meiosis I or II which causes you to either lose or gain a chromosome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Plants are able to tolerate increases in chromosomes which is often lethal to mammals. This is caused by the fact that the plants reproduce asexually. This allows plants to balance out when a chromosomes are lost or gained. Another gamete of the same type can form and will combine with the other which will allow homologous pairing.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonA[comment] Since people do not want to eat seeds with their fruit generally, polyploids are very often seen in plant life. In nature, plants that are polyploid do not form seeds which makes them great commercially.
phenomenonB Increases or decreases in the X chromosome have little effect on human phenotype.
phenomenonB[comment] I think this is very interesting because with most autosomal abnormalities you can have a very small chromosomal change result in a large change phenotypically, such as in trisomy-21 (Down Syndrome). However, the X chromosome is very tolerant of extra chromosomes and often people lead normal lives with extra X's.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Life cycles depend on sexual determination, and in humans this means X and Y chromosomes. The Y chromosome causes maleness, a drastic change in phenotype, but the X chromosome can be thought of as the default.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Autosomal aneuploidy is the increase or decrease in a autosomal chromosome. It is rare in humans and mammals because most are spontaneously aborted. Specific scenarios in humans include Trisomy 21, 13 and 18.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Plants survive aneuploidy better than do humans. Autopolyploids have duplications of the same genome. Allopolyploids have doubling of the chromosomes in a hybrid of two different species. Desirable crops with this genetic change are strawberries because they are larger and cannot be copied, bananas so they do not have seeds, and flowering plants.
phenomenonA Plants tolerate increases in both single chromosomes and entire sets of chromosomes. Historically, increases in entire sets of chromosomes has resulted in many of the crop plants used today.
phenomenonA[comment] Plants with increases in entire sets of chromosomes are sometimes sterile if they have unbalanced genes. This is important so that the company can sell the plants as larger versions without their genetic work being stolen .
phenomenonB Autosomal anueploidy is rare in mammals and in humans occurs in very specific scenarios.
phenomenonB[comment] Human autosomal aneuploidy usually results in a spontaneous abortion. This connects to evolution. Sterile or dysfunctional children is not desirable for fitness of a population.
